A woman’s ability to safely deliver vaginally is predicted by the size of her pelvic inlet and outlet. 
Using the pelvis and your fingers, define the following dimensions     . 
The pelvic inlet is defined by the:
maximum transverse diameter of the inlet (A), and the
sagittal inlet (B), measured between the sacral promontory and the top of the pubic symphysis.
The pelvic outlet is defined by the: 
bispinous outlet (C), the distance between the ischial spines, which is the narrowest lateral dimension of the pelvic outlet, and the 
sagittal outlet (D), the distance between the coccyx and the bottom of the pubic symphysis
22A   The Difference Between the Male and Female Pelves

Largely to accommodate childbirth, the female pelvis is different from the male pelvis.
The pelvis in the female has a larger, more circular pelvic inlet; that of the male pelvis is often described as, “heart shaped”, because the sacral promontory impinges on the pelvic inlet from the posterior aspect. 
The distance between the ischial spines is the narrowest point in the birth canal. This dimension is smaller in men, because the ischial spines in the male pelvis are more prominent and project more medially into the true pelvis. 
The infrapubic angle is larger in women than in men. This results in greater separation of the ischial tuberosities, which widens the pelvic outlet for passage of a baby
